{"cursor":"20114","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nAn 'accretion disc' is a structure (often a circumstellar disk) formed by\ndiffuse material in orbital motion around a central body. The central body is\ntypically a star. Gravity causes material in the disc to spiral inward towards\nthe central body. Gravitational forces compress the material causing the\nemission of electromagnetic radiation. The frequency range of that radiation\ndepends on the central object. Accretion discs of young stars and protostars\nradiate in the infrared; those around neutron stars and black holes in the X-ray\npart of the spectrum. The study of accretion discs is called\n'diskoseismology'.\n","linknr":340,"url":"Accretion_disk","recorded":1362268758,"links":48,"instances":["fluid_dynamics","science","astrophysics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Binary stars|-","Black holes","Unsolved problems in physics","Vortices"],"headings":["Manifestations","Accretion disc physics","Analytic models of sub-Eddington accretion discs (thin discs, ADAFs)","Analytic models of super-Eddington accretion discs (slim discs, Polish doughnuts)","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Accretion_disk.jpg/250px-Accretion_disk.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/2/b/a2b6240df9f6a395cc1275eccc584290.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/d/b9d99db8626de63193c7fe96273a6cae.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/1/e/e1e1d3d40573127e9ee0480caf1283d6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/2/3/623466cb949339dabc06adcd88718562.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/3/0/530bd9f3916ec71e18f6a394647e78ad.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/1/d/c1d9f50f86825a1a2302ec2449c17196.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/c/e/3cec19fafca9c41860d3a